title: For Sale:  Walther PPQ Navy 4.6 SD 9MM - NIB Never Fired
postcontent:
One of the most popular polymer guns out there today.  The Walther PPQ is a short recoil-operated locked breech semi-automatic pistol that uses a modified Browning cam-lock system adapted from the Hi-Power pistol. The PPQ has a glassfiber-reinforced polymer frame and steel slide assembly. It can be broken down into its main parts or field stripped with a take down catch without the help of tools. The internal preset striker 'Quick Defense' trigger of the PPQ is a departure of previous Walther pistols and has been developed for the PPQ.[9] When the trigger is pulled the trigger bar engages a disconnect lever, which props up a sear hook, which releases the fully pre-loaded striker assembly, firing the pistol. Pulling the trigger does not partially load the striker spring as with the Glock and many other striker fired pistol designs. The PPQ trigger pull is entirely due to the trigger and disconnector springs. The PPQ has a trigger travel of approximately 9 mm (0.4 in) with a relatively short trigger reset of 2.5 mm (0.1 in) and a trigger pull of approximately 25 N (5.6 lbf). Unlike many other trigger systems, preset internal strikers have a let-off point and trigger pull that remains unchanged from the first shot to the last and requires no decocker. It should however be noted that the striker of the PPQ variant does not protrude from the back of the slide, as the firearm is in a constant cocked state.  Shipping to your FFL in legal states for $30.

title: For Sale:  Professional Knife Sharpening
postcontent:
I'm located in the Birmingham area and would like to offer my professional knife sharpening service to you for a very reasonable cost. When Bass Pro Shop will charge you $20 to have someone with no experience run your blade through an electric sharpener and take years of metal off your blade, why not have someone who has several years of hand sharpening experience and an intense attention to detail to handle your blades? Not only will you pay about the same, but your blades will be exponentially sharper (scary sharp), will look very aesthetically pleasing, and all with as little metal removal as possible. I'm an engineer in my day job and am naturally OCD about things, including my and your blades so I highly recommend not leaving your good knives with someone with a powered sharpener at the gun show or flea market.

I take all folding and fixed blade knives to a 30,000 grit, mirror-polished finish that is beyond the definition of scary sharp---hair-whittling actually. Kitchen knives are finished at 1000 grit for a toothier edge better suited for cutting food. (Some professional chefs do prefer a finer edge and can be done by request) 

Folding and fixed blade knives:
5" and under - $25
Over 5" - $35

Kitchen knives:
Standard 1000 grit - $2 per inch
"The Works" 30k grit - $5 per inch

Tanto blades or odd, double bevel knives:
$10 adder per blade

Yes, I do sharpen serrated blades. Things I do not sharpen include hair cutting shears and woodworking tools since I'm frequently asked about those. 

Rates above can vary on a per case basis based on if the blade is very damaged or if there are special requests. 

Similar mail-in services online can cost over $50 for one knife plus the cost of shipping and days or weeks being without your knives. I'm centrally located in the Hoover area and can arrange drop-off and pickup of your knives, always in a timely fashion and with the utmost care. Feel free to email me with any questions, and if you don't live locally, ask about sharpening by mail.
